ntry. We had an old shed outside that housed tools and things, lots of things that would be very dangerous to a six year old child. Because, of the danger, though I didn't understand this at the time, I was forbidden to go to the shed.<br>
<br>
I never really even wanted to go to the shed, until something happened. I overheard my dad saying at the dinner table that a kitty cat had crawled into the shed somehow, and had a litter of kittens. Now, ever since before I can remember, I have been a big animal lover, thus why I wanted to be a druid, and I wanted to go and see and play with those kittens more than anything in the world.<br>
<br>
I held back the urge about as long as a six year old could, two or three days, until I finally caved in to free will, and when nobody was around I snuck out to the shed to play with the kittens. As I expected, they were cute and warm and fuzzy, and ofcourse they loved to have their soft fur rubbed. And they loved to play with strings and leaves, but alas I knew I must make haste so as not to be discovered, and I left almost as quickly as I had come.<br>
<br>
That evening, my father came into my room, with the look on his face that meant trouble, I knew that somehow he had discovered that I went to the shed. How could he know? I wondered. I had left no visible evidence.<br>
<br>
He began to inform me that I had been disobediant, and that I would be punished shortly, but first he wanted to tell me what had happened to let him know I was there.<br>
<br>
It seems, sadly, that in my haste to return to the house unnoticed, I neglected to see one of the small kittens trying to follow me out the door, when I pulled the door shut, the kitten was caught in it and crushed, and killed.<br>
<br>
I was devistated, how could I have performed such an act, even if unknowingly it was indeed horrid. I cried for the rest of the night, and for a week after.<br>
<br>
This was the first encounter I had in life with death, of any creature, and still to this day it saddens me to remember this incident.<br>
<br>
Things in EQ get heated sometimes, tempers flare we get angry, we feel cheated, we begin to despise people, sometimes even entire groups of people. We can't help this, it's human nature, it's part of comtetition. But as frustrated as I may get sometimes, I am so thankful that I even have the ability to play EQ. I'm thankful for all the friends I have made in it, Friends I would have never known existed otherwise. I am even thankful for the people that don't like me for without you the game would not be as interesting.<br>
<br>
Dunno why I posted this, I was just bored and thought of that day, I felt bad so I came here to let it out.  <p>Pictures are worth a thousand words. Someone asked me to shutup so I took down my picture. Now my posts are all 1000 words less.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubrumpybronzefinger.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Brumpy Bronzefinger</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Tad-pole</span><br>  Posts: 56<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(11/30/01 8:38:21 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ftherathetravelagencyfrm15.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Bored.....</span><hr size=1> /comfort<br>
